data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count check with meaningful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific element exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — reports *"Expected 3, got 5"* instead of just *"false"*
- **Add message parameters** — when `Assert.IsTrue` is unavoidable, add a description
- **`CollectionAssert`** — use for richer collection checks:

```csharp
// Check collection contains specific items
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// Check two collections have the same elements
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expectedList, actualList);

// Check all items are of a type
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Check no nulls
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
```

- **Avoid `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)`** — use `Assert.IsNotNull(x)` instead

The general rule: use the **most specific assertion** available. It produces better diagnostics on failure.
